Description: Fragment of amygdaloid handle of Egyptian pottery transport amphora. Clay near fine light brown with some mica. Lightly impressed stamp with plumed cartouche.
Findspot: Found/Acquired: Cemetery (Naukratis) (Is this or 739 indicated as from the cemetery in the Register? Both seem odd.)
Curator's comments: This was the only stamp registered from Naukratis at the time of acquisition, but was overlooked until 2011, probably because it had been stored separately from the other ceramic material from Naukratis. Cartouches are more often stamped on jar-sealings in the Late Period. See examples from Tell Dafana: jar-sealing with plumed cartouche of Nekau with the title "son of Ra" inside cartouche (EA 23793) and jar-sealing with plumed cartouche of Amasis (EA 23795) For a seal in situ on a jar, see EA 22356. See also a seal in bronze with plumed cartouche of Amasis including the title of "perfect god" (EA 23903). It was found in Tell Dafana and was probably used to stamp amphoras, usually jar-sealings as aforementioned (Petrie 1888, p. 77 § 76, p. 111, pl. xli, 76). Petrie, W.M. F. 1888. Tanis 2: Nebesheh (Am) and Defenneh (Tahpanhes). London: Truebner & Co.
Bibliographic references: Villing et al 2013-2015 / Naukratis: Greeks in Egypt (JB.1310)
